“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, a country without a coastline, hopes the court will open the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rig-covered naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings raise a sea blue flag.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are decorated with the motto: “We have the right to the sea.
It is our duty to recover it.”
The entire inland state of Bolivia still remembers the coastline they lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century, and the country longs to once again sail the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be greater than they have been for decades, as Bolivia awaits an International Court of Justice ruling on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has drive, community spirit and peace of mind, and of course awaits the outcome with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling of the International Court of Justice on a large screen in many different parts of the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim that Chile – after decades of sporadic negotiations – is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia a separate outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic native president – who faces a controversial re-election campaign next year – has also staked heavily on Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to a return to the Pacific,” he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to take the side of Bolivia, and that very little would change if it had.
The UN agency, like the team in the Netherlands, has no authority to allow them to give away Chilean land, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
That the ruling of the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the last arguments were heard indicates that the case “was not complicated,” according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And rather than advancing Bolivia’s cause, the past four years may actually have made things worse.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
She believes that Morales' antagonistic rhetoric has devoured any remaining goodwill on Chile's side.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the negotiations on some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the matter after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Velzé, Bolivia’s representative at The Hague, rejected the theory that the court’s decision came unusually quickly.
According to him, Monday will give Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new generation of relations with Chile” and the opportunity to “put an end to 139 years of disagreement, for the benefit of both parties.”
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – has used the maritime situation as a political cover-up.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to have access to the Pacific," he added.
“Knowledge is an opportunity to see what we have to do to overcome the past.”
