John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Scotland’s free schools continue to demonstrate academic excellence, and this has persisted in 2018 with another year of outstanding exam results, supported by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools, these schools employ more than 30,000 students across Scotland and work hard to deliver the very best school experience to both students and parents.
Free schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their position as world citizens.
As an educational body that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages are increasingly a popular and in-demand elective in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the words reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we see that languages are at the top of the table with the highest passing percentages from free schools.
A total of 68 per cent of pupils who studied foreign languages received the exam grade A.
The data, obtained from the 74 member schools of the Free School Council, showed that 72 per cent of students received an A in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of those who studied German, 69 per cent of those who studied French and 63 per cent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This illustrates that free schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a crucial skill children and young people are undoubtedly going to need in the future.
Languages as subject choices are now valued at the same level as natural sciences such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics on the curriculum for free schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 showed that of the reasons employers stated for having difficulty filling a vacancy, 17% could be attributed to lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities require language skills, these skills become essential in a globalized world.
If you have learned a second language, these lifelong skills will bring real benefits in the future, no matter what career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey answered by more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language a two-digit number of participants (15 percent) could speak.
This is why investing in language learning is now crucial for today’s children.
Knowing more languages, especially those associated with emerging economies, will give children better opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland if each school teaches in different languages.
Many schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most valuable to the UK on their way to 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever interests your child, there will always be a choice of languages to choose from at free schools, with teachers who are experts in this field.
Scottish schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the knowledge and skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied in today’s global business environment that languages are constantly crucial to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Free schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and distinction to Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
