North Korea will “in no way” agree to unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions strengthened suspicion of the United States and that it would in no way agree to unilaterally relinquish its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly that North Korea has undertaken “significant goodwill efforts” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and promising not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We have not seen a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, we have no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to gradual nuclear disarmament, with North Korea being rewarded for gradual disarmament steps, but his statement was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump issued in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a incumbent president of the United States and a North Korean leader, in which Kim pledged to work toward “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the Korean War from 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce severe international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first’ and raises the pressure via sanctions to achieve its goal by force, even opposing the ‘declaration on the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can put us on our knees is a dream come true for people who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions create further mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second hit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed before the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: “If the other party to this disarmament issue were South Korea, rather than the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have been as locked up as it is.”
However, the tone of Ris’ speech was very different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that an attack on the mainland by North Korea’s missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
After threatening to “completely destroy” North Korea last year, this year Trump stood before the UN and praised Kim for being brave enough to take disarmament steps, but said much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is nuclear-defused.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a timeframe for this, saying, “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
