Harvard Students Take Courses in Getting Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will help students get more sleep by tackling the growing uncultured memorization of the night with caffeine drinks as fuel.
An academic found that students at the world’s best university often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why has no one said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to the students how important it is to have good sleep habits in order to perform academically and athletically, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and president of the university’s health services, said that the university decided to start the course after they saw students suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for an hour, has a series of interactive exercises.
In one section, there is a picture of a room in a dormitory, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books and hear about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important a sleep routine is.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of campuses with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this is not going to change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know about this, just as you have a right to know about the risks of smoking,” Professor Czeisler said.
There is still a certain pride in being able to study all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Enough and good sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even as a means of weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, leading to constant hunger sensations.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course, taking one of the professor’s classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course inspired him to work for a course that was available to the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar study programme before enrolling at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm for when to go to bed as well as for when to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic displays and LED lights. This type of light can disrupt circadian rhythms and lead to insomnia.
