The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affect breeding sites and the reduction of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to locate insects and obstacles on their way as they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
